      "writtenOn": "2018-09-13T20:48:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Does this mean we might have an INFRA_FAILED build/step that has a \"future\" start_time (relative to end_time), or that we might have an INFRA_FAILED build/step that does not have a start_time?\n\n(If the latter, that would be sad because INFRA_FAILED is a terminal step, meaning it has an end_time, and end_times must follow start_times)",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 46,
        "startChar": 37,
        "endLine": 46,
        "endChar": 71
      },
      "revId": "72d126a5ae71cea770a74853cf31cbdd09bcfe38",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "396dfe48_e19d09bb",
        "filename": "buildbucket/proto/common.proto",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 46,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-13T21:21:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it means \"we might have an INFRA_FAILED build/step that does not have a start_time\". Also I\u0027ve added end_time\u003e\u003dstart_time constraint to both build and step.\n\nyeah, it is the case today. Imagine a build has expired (no bot to serve it). It has creation time and we know the moment when we expired it.\n\nThere is also cancelation. start_time is not required if build was cancelled. It might have been cancelled before it started. But we always know when the build has reached its terminal state.\n\nwdyt",
      "parentUuid": "d830fffc_377e42cb",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 46,
        "startChar": 37,
        "endLine": 46,
        "endChar": 71
      },
      "revId": "72d126a5ae71cea770a74853cf31cbdd09bcfe38",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
